******
[2] Philippines (Mindanao)
Date: Sat 14 Jul 2007
Source: Inquirer.net [edited]
<http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/breakingnews/regions/view_article.php?article_id=76651>

The typhoid fever outbreak that has affected at least 6 villages in
Santa Cruz, Davao del Sur [Province], has been traced to a spring
water-impounding project where residents draw their drinking water,
officials said on Sat 14 Jul 2007.
Mahelinde Colminares, Davao del Sur health chief, said water samples
taken from the spring in 'sitio Ragobrob' in Saliducon village turned
out positive for the bacterium that causes typhoid fever. "The water
from that spring is not potable," she said.
Colminares said that because of this, they have advised residents of
barangay [district] Zone 1, Zone 2, Zone 3, Zone 4, Tuban, and
Tagabuli to refrain from drawing water there.
At least 200 people have been affected by the outbreak that started 3
weeks ago. She said if they have no other sources, they should first
boil the water tapped from the spring before drinking it.
Asked about the possible cause of the contamination, Colminares said
they found out that residents near the spring failed to practice
proper waste disposal. She said bacteria that grow on human waste
could seep underground and contaminate water sources, especially if
these are near the surface.
[Byline: Eldie Aguirre, Orlando Dinoy]
--
